  • WiikeyFusion clone from Badassconsole
  • SD Gecko support
  • No Motherboard cut (the mobo should fit without cutting it)
  • Wall power/Batteries switch
  • Headphones plug.
  • Integrated memory card
  • Player 2 port
  • Original power supply port

I'll post a list of parts if you guys are intrested. Here is a link of the whole building process detailed with pictures and stuff (not a tutorial as things have changed on the design overtime) : http://forums.modretro.com/viewtopic.php?f=36&t=14567

description.text:
The original polypropylene feet that came with our Ikea Tobias chairs weared down after some years of intensive use (to be honest, our kitchen floor is quite irregular, maybe this helped).

Finally the remaining plastic thickness became so small that the head of the fixing rivets was exposed and started to scratch our floor tiles, so I decided to replace them with 3d printed ABS feet.

They are designed to replace the original parts, adding some height to increase lifetime. I suppose the wearing rate will depend on the kind of material you choose, I have used ABS (100% infill) with good results - the first prototypes have been installed and heavily used for 2 months now and they are still as new.

To remove the old feet you will have to drill out the original aluminium rivets and fix the new ones using 4.8 mm rivets (I used standard aluminium pop rivets, with a body diameter of approximately 4.8 mm and a flange diameter that is roughly two times the diameter of the rivet body).

===============================================================

Las bases de polipropileno que venían de origen con nuestras sillas Tobias de Ikea se han ido degradando tras varios años de uso intensivo (seguramente ha tenido algo que ver el hecho de que el suelo de nuestra cocina es muy irregular).

Finalmente el grosor del plástico se ha vuelto tan reducido que las cabezas de los remaches de sujección han comenzado a rayar las losetas del suelo, así que decidí reemplazarlas con piezas de ABS impresas.

Las he diseñado para reemplazar las bases originales, añadiendo algo de grosor para incrementar su vida útil. Supongo que el ritmo de desgaste dependerá del material que elijas para imprimirlas, yo he usado ABS sólido (relleno 100%) con buenos resultados. Los primeros prototipos fueron instalados hace ya varios meses, han sido utilizados intensivamente, y continúan como nuevos.

Para retirar las bases originales tendréis que taladrar los viejos remaches. Luego podréis fijar las nuevas utilizando remaches de 4.8 mm (yo he usado remaches normales de aluminio, con un diámetro del cuerpo de unos 4.8 mm y un diámetro de la cabeza de aproximadamente el doble).

This version of my Advanced Word Pen, is ready to accept the widely available Bic ball pen inner. The pen body is rounded making it comfortable to write with. The output file includes a fitted cap and helper tabs to prevent the print from lifting off the build-plate during printing. The pen length scales according to the text length which is automatically centred. I am still doping the print with the pen inner to ensure a snug fit - see instructions.

I have been successfully printing this pen with ReplicatorG and Sailfish firmware by taking advantage of the Sailfish [email protected] function. Successful printing requires precise measurement of your filament diameter to ensure the cap and ball-point inner fit snugly. I still dope the print with the pen inner to ensure a snug fit. I created a duplicate profile and edited the start.gcode to add M322 Z4.5 to the bottom of the file. This tells the sailfish firmware to pause at 4.5mm. You can obviously pause the printer manually, or set the zpos position using the printer control interface, but if you plan to print a lot of pens, creating a custom profile in ReplicatorG is the way to go. I have included a sample ReplicatorG/Sailfish profile for the Replicator 2 that includes this modification and fine tuned settings for printing these pens. The Bic ball pen cartridges I am using are from a standard Bic ball pen. I purchased an economy packet of 25 Bic ball pens from my local office supply store for about $10.

Insert the nuts into the slotted holes, 5 on the bottom and 2 from the top if you want to mount the second holder in front. They should fit in with just a little force, make sure to push them down all the way!

Dakanzla created a great box to store all the tiles and pieces for the 3D printed Settler of Catan game. Seeing his design I've got an idea of another design so I'm trying to make it reel. It uses less plastic and take advantage of the form of the tiles to be modular as you have more or less tiles depending on the games extensions and scenarios.

This box is made for Dakanzla's Catan tiles set: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1238980

You have to print the rings from Dakanzla's box as well to fit them in this box: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1482713

If you can't print a 20cm high design go check the 15cm version: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1507682

The basic set can be extended as you wish with the hook system and all the variant. You can use the full set (7 hexa or 6 triangle), add parts or use less part or even use them alone.

Do not print the variant named files. Those are there only to show possible result!

What kind of set do you want to use?

Before downloading and printing you have to ask yourself how your set have to look!
There are basics combinations and then it's up to you.

Basic hexa

For this set you'll need:

  • 1 hexa center
  • 6 hexa basic

You can chose between the big cap to close it or the mid cap with 6 borders cap.

Basic triangle

For this set you'll need:

  • 6 triangle basic

You can chose between the big cap to close it or the mid cap with 6 borders cap.

Individual

You can print any hexa or triangle to make an individual box. You'll just have to print the individual cap corresponding.

Custom

There are a lot of custom combination you can make using the additional hexa or triangle. These new parts have different hooks combinations to adapt to what you want to do.

If you can't make your custom set due to a missing variant you can just ask!

I'm still developping this box system, adding parts and making better one... and I'm always taking advices or suggestions!

title: Gas Filter system for ABS fumes (Air Scrubber)

description.text:
Description

This set of part is a gas filtration system for ABS fumes.
Also called Air Scrubber by some people.

The principle

This system will pull the air through the gas filter cartridge.
It's compatible with standard 3M gas cartridge and will only work by pulling the air through the cartridge. Pushing the air through won't work.
A blower fan turbine is adapted to this kind of application as it's designed to pull the air from one side and compress it to the other side.
The generated air pressure ensure that the air can only go one way.

The system

This system is modular and can be adapted on several types of turbines.

  • Gaz_Mask_Valve.stl is the main part of the system. It allows to connect the 3M cartridge directly to a 5015S turbine.

As those turbine might not be powerful enough you can print an adapter to connect a more powerful one

  • Gaz_Mask_Valve_7530S+GAMMA30.stl
    This part can support both GAMMA30 blower fan, very powerful but a little bit noisy.
    It can also support 7530S or 7515S blower fan. Slightly less powerful but more silent than the GAMMA30 bower fan.

These fans are 12V blower fan, so easy to use.
You can also drive them using PWM module which will allow you to adjust the speed of the fans.

  • GAMMA30_Grid.stl is a grid to protect the output of the blower fan

What filter to choose

Not all gas filter will do, but from our study on this topic (which is mainly in french for now)
FR: https://github.com/3DModularSystems/Scalar/raw/master/Documentation/Etudes/GazFilter/Quel%20filtre%20%C3%A0%20air%20choisir%20pour%20votre%20imprimante.pdf

We can say that

  • A type filters will filter 80% of the known particles.
  • AB type filter will increase the range of filtered particles
  • ABEK type filters will more likely also filter unknown particles generated by colorant or other components added into the filaments by the manufacturer.

How long can last your filter?

This information is provided by the manufacturer of the filter when you by them.
As there is no way to detect that a gas filter has to be changed, a quick trick is to check if you have any smell . This will tell you that your gas cartridge has to be changed.

Where to find the filters

*You can find 9733 blower fans compatible with this unit here: http://3dmodularsystems.com/en/spare-parts/392-9733-12vdc-brussless-blower-fan-3500-rpm-283-cfm.html

  • You can find 7530S blower fans here: http://3dmodularsystems.com/en/spare-parts/143-ventilateur-a-turbine-7530s-12vdc-brussless-avec-cable-de-20cm.html
  • You can find 5015S blower fans here: http://3dmodularsystems.com/en/electronic/68-ventilateur-a-turbine-5015s-12vdc-brussless-avec-cable-de-20cm.html
  • You can find ABEK1P3 3M filter cartridge here: http://3dmodularsystems.com/en/misc/144-3m-gaz-filter-abek1p3.html

However you should be able to find some in our local hardware store, in near the painting tools and protection section of the store.

Have a great printing experience.

Well. I knew for a while that there were a new design for the parts of the lewihe play. I could only see pics, Couldn't find the designs anywere. For now this will have to serve, it has been a nightmare to deal with the damned .STLs.

HINT: To drive the washers and the bearings in place insert them in a piece of flexible filament, then insert the endpoints of the filament into the part holes and like if you were sewing, tense the filament. title: SCOUTcorexy 3D Printer (square aluminum tube frame, scout-tower-like corner nodes, dual-support Z, lots of adjustability to compensate for construction errors)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Check latest version @ https://skfb.ly/Uuv7

!!WARNING: this is a WIP project and will take a lot of time on my side to finish due to ... life. I will often update it and correct it so come back often :).

Update 20170614: Added the .rsdoc source file for you to play with.

Navigate the 3D Model @ SketchFab:
https://skfb.ly/Uuv7

This is a CoreXY 3D printer design that has some features that should be appealing to many:

1) it uses tubular extrusion (square 20x20mm) Aluminum or Steel so it should be cheaper than T/V-slot but all parts are designed to be able to be fitted on 2020 extrusion also;;

2) all the cutting & drilling can be done by hand as the design is very forgiving, prefect straight cuts being unnecessary and perfectly matching holes are not a prerequisite;

3) all frame holes can be drilled by hand with a method I will describe when I will have built it and I release the docs (or can be drilled on a drill press according to the holes pattern I will release when ready). Holes can be slightly larger than the intended size bolts - I use M6 bolts which means holes can be M7;

4) all the features of the printer are mobile, they slide on the tube via the square clamp that I have designed and which is a part of every part in the design;

5) Y rods are adjustable in 3D space due to the 4-points-adjusting-collars that I have designed specifically to take any misalignment of the frame and/or other errors in construction. Like I said, it's quite forgiving;

6) Z axis is dual supported, using 3 smooth rods (10mm) and has a very simple T(ee) support frame from the same square alu tubing. The important aspect of the Z is that the BearingBlocks/Bed_Clamps/Leveling&ShockAbsorbers are all embedded in a 3-part piece that can also take a lot of misalignment of the Z rods (drilling exact holes with the hand drill is impossible so I had to fix this in the design intent so you don't have to outsource any fabrication step).

Another important aspect of the Z axis is that the upper ends of the rods are inserted straight in holes in metal while the lower ends are floating in larger then their diameter holes so that perfect vertical alignment can be done -again using the 4 bolts in the collar of the lower receiving part). Once the verticality is ensured, resin can be poured in these holes to freeze the position.

Update 13/10/2016: I have uploaded the latest "RepStrap-ed" version of the original, with updated parts where better details were developed. This repstrap is due to the expensive price 3DHubs charge for the 3D printed parts and because I don't have my own printer to make them myself. The repstrap pieces are simple ALU angle pieces drilled so they are very easy to make and they use leftover aluminum angle that is used for the bed support (see 3D model). This is for now the basis for the SCOUTcorexy MotelT.

Update 01/06/2016: Another major overhaul: changed size to allow standard dimensions for belts (now a 5m roll is enough for both XY - <1.5m each - and Z - <2m -). To allow this change there have been some parts alterations (ex YRods clamps, ZRods Bearings housing and bumper pieces, etc)

Update 04/07/2016: I have uploaded the different sections' STLs in separate files, with parts arranged on bed with the right orientation for best printing. Now they are ready to be printed.

Update 26/04/2016: Pretty major change in XY Motors Support ALU tubes position (moved them to the exterior, making the frame symmetrical) and XY Motors Mounts (pictures attached). Also Updated all printed parts file.

Update 19/04/2016: Lots of fixes and streamlining of parts. New Floating Parts STL attached. Also check it @Sketchfab for a better experience: https://skfb.ly/MZR8

Update 15/04/2016: Major overhaul of the Z stage
I have updated the bearing blocks to better follow the square clamp design that all other parts feature. For some reason I didn't do this from the beginning and now it bit my backside. STL and Sketchfab models have been updated accordingly.

This "thing" is a filament guide for the Thing-O-Matic, requiring no modifications to the machine body. It simply snaps in place of any of your ToMs' top guide-rod openings (uncovered, of course), depending on the location of your spool holder. My ToM's Z-axis motor wires run into the back/right opening at the top of my ToM, so I designed this guide with a channel for those wires. Your adaptation of this model may require repositioning that channel, or simply adding that channel to all sides of the model (it's up to you... hey, it's a free world here). This "upgrade" or "modification" piece was designed to snap into any of your ToMs' top guide-rod openings. My print did not "snap" in, but fit well. The base of the model works very well, but the guide arms need to be fully reworked. After using this in conjunction with my own filament spool holder, I now know the geometry needed to make this part work. The guide arms need to be removed & completely redesigned (they are backwards, and their size needs to be increased). THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS!!! PRINT THIS PART AT YOUR OWN RISK & WASTE OF PLASTIC! I have printed this object with success, but it does not meet my requirements yet(and probably not yours). This "thing" works, but the arched guide arms do nothing & tend to put a lot of uneccessary stress on the "A" axis (filament drive stepper motor) of my Gen-4 ToM. (My filament spool holder needs a bearing, and my filament guide needs the proper geometry.) Yes, this filament holder works (at least the center part works), but the guide arms need to be reversed (per Z axis) so that they hold the filament UP instead of DOWN... (and repositioned somewhat) and they could be a bit thicker, for sure! (If you don't trust me, go ahead and print this object. You'll see.) Everything but the guide arms work great! Version 2 is located here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15066

Do not print without reading this entire post. You'll just waste plastic. Feel free to modify this design: A) guide arms are of the wrong size & basically upside down, B) clips to not clip into the Thing-O-Matic well, and need to be changed somewhat (or may be my Skeinforge settings? My CAD model shows it gripping the edges of the openings, but my actual print barely did), C) the guide arms do not need to be arched, they can be straight or 45-degrees from the base. Updated version is at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15066 I'm only keeping this design on Thingiverse.com in order to others to see my design progression. Sometimes I think it's helpful for others (especially non-3D types) to see how a real-world design is created. It doesn't always happen the first time. :( I wish it did! :)
